# Phase 10 — Service Certification, Hardcoded IPs & Isolated Second NIC

## Goal

In this phase, the goal was to start the next vSRO services after GlobalManager and understand why MachineManager, GatewayServer and other services were not staying connected.

The main focus was:

```text
CertServer
GlobalManager
MachineManager
vSRO service certification
runtime IP identity
hardcoded EXE IPs
isolated VM networking
```

---

# 1. Initial Situation

CertificationServer and GlobalManager were already working.

However, when starting MachineManager, GatewayServer or FarmManager, the GlobalManager showed errors like:

```text
cannot certify server body : [MachineManager][25.73.87.49]
cannot certify server body : [GatewayServer][192.168.122.198]
cannot certify server body : [FarmManager][192.168.122.198]
```

This meant:

```text
The service could reach GlobalManager,
but GlobalManager rejected the service identity.
```

So the problem was not simply a missing network connection.

The problem was the internal certification identity.

---

# 2. Important Difference: Config IP vs Runtime IP

A very important lesson was:

```text
The IP written in config files is not always the IP used at runtime.
```

Some vSRO executables contain hardcoded IP addresses inside the EXE itself.

That means:

```text
server.cfg can be correct,
packt.dat can be rebuilt,
but the EXE can still send another IP.
```

This was exactly the case here.

---

# 3. Checking Running Processes

To verify if services were actually running, this command was used:

```cmd
tasklist | findstr Manager
```

What it does:

```text
tasklist
```

lists all running Windows processes.

```text
findstr Manager
```

filters the output and only shows processes containing the word `Manager`.

Example result:

```text
GlobalManager.exe
MachineManager.exe
```

This proves whether the process is actually running.

---

Another useful command:

```cmd
tasklist | findstr Server
```

What it does:

```text
Shows running server processes such as GatewayServer, AgentServer or CertificationServer.
```

This is important because the GlobalManager GUI can show planned topology nodes even when the real EXE is not running.

---

# 4. Checking Network Ports

To verify real TCP ports and connections, this command was used:

```cmd
netstat -ano
```

What it does:

```text
Shows active TCP/UDP connections, listening ports and process IDs.
```

Important columns:

```text
Local Address   = local IP and port
Remote Address  = connected remote IP and port
State           = LISTENING / ESTABLISHED / CLOSED
PID             = process ID
```

---

To check a specific port:

```cmd
netstat -ano | findstr 32000
```

What it does:

```text
Shows only network entries containing port 32000.
```

This was used to verify the CertificationServer.

Expected example:

```text
127.0.0.1:32000 LISTENING
127.0.0.1:32000 ESTABLISHED
```

Meaning:

```text
LISTENING    = server is waiting for connections
ESTABLISHED  = active TCP connection exists
```

---

Other useful checks:

```cmd
netstat -ano | findstr 16274
```

What it does:

```text
Checks whether services using port 16274 are listening or connected.
```

```cmd
netstat -ano | findstr 24523
```

What it does:

```text
Checks whether services using port 24523 are listening or connected.
```

These commands are important because they prove real network state, not just GUI state.

