# 5. Searching for Hardcoded IPs

A recursive search was used to find old IP addresses inside files:

```cmd
findstr /S /M "25.73.87.49" *.*
```

What it does:

```text
/S
```

searches through all subfolders.

```text
/M
```

prints only filenames that contain the searched text.

```text
"25.73.87.49"
```

is the old hardcoded IP.

```text
*.*
```

means search all files.

Result:

```text
MachineManager.exe
AgentServer.exe
SR_GameServer.exe
```

This proved that the old IP was inside the executables themselves.

---

Later, the same method was used for another IP:

```cmd
findstr /S /M "192.168.1.121" *.*
```

This showed:

```text
MachineManager.exe
```

Meaning:

```text
Even the replacement MachineManager.exe contained a hardcoded IP.
```

---

# 6. Why Config Changes Alone Did Not Work

The config files were changed and `packt.dat` was rebuilt, but MachineManager still reported the old IP.

This proved:

```text
The runtime identity was not only loaded from config files.
```

Instead, MachineManager sent an IP from inside the executable.

Important conclusion:

```text
Config layer != executable layer
```

The service identity can come from:

```text
server.cfg
packt.dat
srNodeType.ini
hardcoded EXE strings
network adapter detection
```

---

# 7. Rebuilding packt.dat

After changing INI/config data, `packt.dat` must be rebuilt.

Command:

```cmd
Convert.exe ini ini dat packt.dat
```

What it does:

```text
Convert.exe
```

runs the vSRO conversion tool.

```text
ini
```

means input format is INI.

```text
ini
```

means input folder is the `ini` folder.

```text
dat
```

means output format is DAT.

```text
packt.dat
```

is the generated output file used by the CertificationServer.

Important:

```text
Editing INI files alone is not enough.
The runtime file packt.dat must be rebuilt.
```

