# 9. Discovery: MachineManager Had Hardcoded Runtime IP

MachineManager kept sending:

```text
MachineManager[25.73.87.49]
```

even after config changes.

After replacing the executable with another version, it sent:

```text
MachineManager[192.168.1.121]
```

This proved:

```text
The runtime identity was coming from the executable.
```

The EXE itself contained an IP address.

---

# 10. Why Simple Hex Editing Was Not Enough

The old hardcoded IP was:

```text
192.168.1.121
```

The desired VM IP was:

```text
192.168.122.198
```

Problem:

```text
192.168.1.121   = 13 characters
192.168.122.198 = 15 characters
```

A longer IP cannot simply be inserted into an EXE without shifting bytes.

That can break the executable.

Conclusion:

```text
Simple hex editing is only safe when the replacement string is the same length or shorter.
```

---

# 11. Final Network Solution

Instead of dangerous binary patching or exposing the VM to the full home network, a second isolated virtual network adapter was added.

Final design:

```text
Adapter 1:
192.168.122.x
Purpose: Internet / NAT / normal VM access

Adapter 2:
192.168.1.121
Purpose: isolated vSRO internal certification identity
```

This solved the problem without:

```text
full bridge networking
unsafe binary patching
exposing the VM to the whole home LAN
```

---

# 12. Creating an Isolated libvirt Network

A new isolated libvirt network was created.

File:

```bash
nano isolated-vsro.xml
```

What it does:

```text
Opens a new XML file in the nano editor.
```

XML content:

```xml
<network>
  <name>vsroisolated</name>
  <bridge name='virbr1'/>
  <ip address='192.168.1.1' netmask='255.255.255.0'>
  </ip>
</network>
```

Explanation:

```text
<name>vsroisolated</name>
```

sets the libvirt network name.

```text
<bridge name='virbr1'/>
```

creates a new virtual bridge interface on the host.

```text
192.168.1.1
```

becomes the host-side IP of this isolated virtual network.

This network is separate from the real home network.

---

Save in nano:

```text
CTRL + O
ENTER
CTRL + X
```

What it does:

```text
CTRL + O  = write/save file
ENTER     = confirm filename
CTRL + X  = exit nano
```

---

# 13. Registering the libvirt Network

Command:

```bash
virsh net-define isolated-vsro.xml
```

What it does:

```text
Registers the XML network definition inside libvirt.
```

---

Command:

```bash
virsh net-start vsroisolated
```

What it does:

```text
Starts the isolated virtual network.
```

---

Command:

```bash
virsh net-autostart vsroisolated
```

What it does:

```text
Makes the isolated network start automatically after host reboot.
```

---

Command:

```bash
virsh net-list --all
```

What it does:

```text
Lists all libvirt networks and shows whether they are active or inactive.
```

Expected:

```text
vsroisolated active
```

---

# 14. Attaching a Second Network Adapter to the VM

Command:

```bash
virsh attach-interface \
  --domain windows10 \
  --type network \
  --source vsroisolated \
  --model e1000e \
  --config \
  --live
```

What it does:

```text
virsh attach-interface
```

adds a new virtual network interface to a VM.

```text
--domain windows10
```

selects the VM named `windows10`.

```text
--type network
```

means the adapter connects to a libvirt virtual network.

```text
--source vsroisolated
```

connects the adapter to the isolated vSRO network.

```text
--model e1000e
```

uses an Intel e1000e virtual network card model.

```text
--config
```

makes the adapter permanent after reboot.

```text
--live
```

adds it immediately while the VM is running.

---

# 15. Checking VM Network Interfaces on Host

Command:

```bash
virsh domiflist windows10
```

What it does:

```text
Shows all virtual network interfaces attached to the VM.
```

Expected final structure:

```text
