# 23. Lessons Learned

## vSRO Networking & Certification

```text
A successful TCP connection does NOT automatically mean successful certification.
```

A service can:
- connect to GlobalManager
- open sockets correctly
- appear in topology

and still fail certification because of identity mismatch.

---

```text
vSRO services can use hardcoded runtime IPs from inside the executable.
```

This means:
- config files may be correct
- packt.dat may be rebuilt
- networking may work

but certification still fails because the EXE sends another IP internally.

---

```text
Config layer and executable layer are separate things.
```

Possible identity sources:

```text
server.cfg
packt.dat
srNodeType.ini
hardcoded EXE strings
network adapter selection
```

---

```text
GlobalManager topology alone is not proof that a service is healthy.
```

Real verification requires:
- tasklist
- netstat
- certification logs

---

```text
tasklist verifies processes.
```

```cmd
tasklist | findstr Manager
```

proves whether the executable itself is running.

---

```text
netstat verifies real TCP state.
```

```cmd
netstat -ano
```

proves:
- listening ports
- established sockets
- real connections

instead of relying on GUI assumptions.

---

```text
findstr can discover hardcoded IPs inside binaries.
```

Example:

```cmd
findstr /S /M "192.168.1.121" *.*
```

This is extremely useful for:
- reverse engineering
- migration debugging
- old private server files
- leaked binaries

---

```text
Inline hex replacement is only safe when the new string is equal length or shorter.
```

Replacing:

```text
192.168.1.121
```

with:

```text
192.168.122.198
```

is dangerous because the new string is longer.

This can:
- corrupt offsets
- break instructions
- damage memory alignment
- crash the executable

---

```text
Binary patching should be avoided unless absolutely necessary.
```

A cleaner architecture is usually better than modifying binaries.

---

```text
A second isolated NIC is an elegant workaround for hardcoded IPs.
```

Advantages:

```text
No dangerous binary editing
No full bridge into home LAN
No exposure of VM to entire network
No runtime instability
```

while still allowing:
- hardcoded identity IPs
- internet access
- NAT isolation

---

```text
Multiple NICs inside a VM can separate responsibilities cleanly.
```

Example:

```text
NIC 1:
Internet / NAT

NIC 2:
Internal service identity
```

This is a common professional virtualization technique.

---

```text
A VM can have internet access and still stay mostly isolated.
```

Using:
- libvirt NAT
- isolated virtual bridges
- dedicated internal subnets

gives far more control than simple bridge mode.

---

```text
Full bridge mode is often unnecessary and less secure.
```

Bridge mode exposes the VM directly into the home LAN.

The isolated dual-NIC approach keeps:
- cleaner separation
- less attack surface
- better control

